                     <interp inst="t18110109-59-person633" type="given" value="James"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18110109-59-person633" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             is my partner, we live at No. <placeName id="t18110109-59-crimeloc351">7, Warner-street, Clerkenwell</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18110109-59-crimeloc351" type="placeName" value="7, Warner-street, Clerkenwell"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18110109-59-crimeloc351" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18110109-59-off348 t18110109-59-crimeloc351"></join>; the prisoner was our <rs id="t18110109-59-deflabel352" type="occupation">porter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18110109-59-defend627 t18110109-59-deflabel352"></join>. On the 21st of December last I was informed by my wife that our porter had been robbing us; I came home in the evening between eleven and twelve o'clock, I went down stairs where the prisoner had a box, I looked in the box and there I saw a pair of gloves of ours.</p>
               <p>GEORGE SAVILLE STAPLES. I am an apprentice to Messrs. Cook and Martin. On the evening of the 21st I was going through the room where the porters box was, the lid of the box was not locked; I looked in it; I turned over a few of the things, I saw a shawl, I knew it to be the pattern of some that we had in our shop; I informed Mrs. Cook of it.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18110109-59-person634">
                  JAMES 
                  HANCOCK
               <interp inst="t18110109-59-person634" type="surname" value="HANCOCK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18110109-59-person634" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18110109-59-person634" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 22d I apprehended the prisoner at Mr. Cook's, he was in the shop crying; when I went in I tied his hands and went down and searched the privy, I found two pieces of a shawl; I searched the prisoner's pocket, I found a quarter of a yard of cambric, which is marked with his master's mark.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The cambric I took from some<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181101090049"></xptr>waste paper that I went to light the fire with.</p>
               <p>The prisoner called one witness, who gave him a good character.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18110109-59-verdict353" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18110109-59-verdict353" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>, aged 18.</p>
